  <h2 class="reveal">A discovery board, not a job board</h2>
  <p class="reveal">Postings land in a local <code>SQLite</code> database and every one runs through a scoring model before I ever see it. So far it has scored <strong>9,600+</strong> of them, and each score can be reproduced from the source data. What surfaces is a ranked board carrying the signals I actually decide on:</p>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li><strong>Tier.</strong> Postings get bucketed by fit: role, seniority, pay signal. An early version was too generous with the top bucket, so I tightened it. Tier 1 dropped from a few thousand to about a hundred, which is what real fit should look like.</li>
    <li><strong>Fraud.</strong> A set of heuristics flags the patterns ghost and scam listings share. That cut the flagged-fraud noise by about 80%, so the board stays honest.</li>
    <li><strong>Freshness.</strong> Every posting is re-verified against its source before it surfaces, so I never spend a morning chasing a role that closed last week.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">A fit report that surfaces gaps instead of faking them</h2>
  <p class="reveal">Pick a job and the system writes a fit report, then drafts a tailored package off it. The report grades every requirement into three honest tiers, and the third one is the whole point:</p>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li><strong>Matched.</strong> Direct, provable overlap between the requirement and my record.</li>
    <li><strong>Equivalent.</strong> Different words, same capability, named explicitly so the mapping is a claim I can stand behind, not a stretch.</li>
    <li><strong>Gap.</strong> Where I don't line up, it says so. A tool that scored everyone a perfect fit would be worthless. This one surfaces gaps instead of faking them, which is the only version I'd let near a real decision.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">A human approves every send</h2>
  <p class="reveal">Nothing goes out on its own. Drafted packages sit in a submission ledger behind a funnel view, and every send is a deliberate human action: I read it, I approve it, it logs. The automation makes the human faster; it never replaces the human. That line, drawn on purpose, is what keeps the whole thing trustworthy:</p>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li>A <strong>re-score pipeline</strong> re-ran every row (5,905 at the time) against the corrected model in one pass with <strong>zero errors</strong>, after backing up first.</li>
    <li>A <strong>test suite</strong> covers the scoring edges, the geo logic, and the fraud heuristics, and it's green before anything ships.</li>
    <li><strong>Data-hygiene guards</strong> clear out orphaned rows and stop half-formed records from moving down the pipeline.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">Why I point to this one</h2>
  <p class="reveal">That's what AI enablement means to me: real workflows, honest guardrails, and adoption you can trust. It's a system that makes a lot of decisions, knows where it might be wrong, and keeps a person in the loop on the ones that matter. I'd rather show evidence than make claims, and that holds for everything I build.</p>
</CaseStudy>

